               <p>521. 
               
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-defend1914" type="defendantName">
                     RICHARD 
                     DEANE
                  <interp inst="t18340220-210-defend1914" type="surname" value="DEANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-defend1914" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-defend1914" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-defend1914" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18340220-210-off1195" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-off1195" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-off1195" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18340220-210-cd1196" type="crimeDate">4th of February</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-210-off1195 t18340220-210-cd1196"></join>, seven yards of velvet, value 2l. 12s., the goods of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18340220-210-victim1916" type="victimName">
                           Thomas 
                           Chester
                        <interp inst="t18340220-210-victim1916" type="surname" value="Chester"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-210-victim1916" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-210-victim1916" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-210-off1195 t18340220-210-victim1916"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , and that he had been before convicted of felony
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1917">
                  WILLIAM 
                  CHESTER
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1917" type="surname" value="CHESTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1917" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1917" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am eleven years old - I know the nature of an oath - I am the brother of Thomas Chester - he lives at No. 1, <placeName id="t18340220-210-crimeloc1197">James-street, Bethnal-green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340220-210-crimeloc1197" type="placeName" value="James-street, Bethnal-green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340220-210-crimeloc1197" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-210-off1195 t18340220-210-crimeloc1197"></join> - he went out about half-past eight o'clock on the morning of the 4th of February - I was left at home - I went out after my brother was gone out, to the end of the window, to see a little boy put some wood into a truck - I am almost certain I left the room door latched when I went into the street; any one could get into the room by lifting up the latch - the little boy who was there told me something, and I saw the prisoner running from our house - I knew him, and called to him, "
               <persName id="t18340220-210-person1918">
                  Dick 
                  Deane
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1918" type="surname" value="Deane"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1918" type="given" value="Dick"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1918" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            " - I think he must have heard me, but he did not answer.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. What did you call after him for? A. Because he was running from my brother's house, and had something under his arm under his coat - I went into the house, and saw my brother's work cut off the roll - I had seen that roll before I went into the street, and it was all<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183402200112"></xptr>right - I was not in the street above five minutes - I did not see anybody else about.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by Mr. PHILLIPS. Q. Does your brother keep pigeons? A. Yes, in the same room - the window is not kept open - there was nobody at home but me- I had been there from half-past eight o'clock - my brother was there then - and he went out - I did not see the prisoner's face - he did not turn round to me - I did not see him come out of the room.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1919">
                  JOHN 
                  COOPER
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1919" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1919" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1919" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Chester that morning, and saw the prisoner come out at the door - he turned and looked both ways - I said to Chester, "Do you know him?" and he called after him several times - he appeared to have a bundle under his coat - he was running.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. How near were you to your friend when the prisoner came out? A. He was on the side of me - the prisoner looked into my face - I am not certain whether the prisoner's coat was buttoned, but there was something sticking out at the back of his coat - it was not like a coat, it was a flat bundle - I cannot tell whether it was in paper, as I could not see through the coat.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1920">
                  MARY 
                  GREENLEAF
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1920" type="surname" value="GREENLEAF"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1920" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1920" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live opposite the prosecutor - I was sweeping my door about nine o'clock that day - I saw the prisoner come out with a bundle, and the boy said,"Dick Deane, what have you got there?"</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Did you see the bundle distinctly? A. Yes - I saw it - I stated at the office that he had the bundle under his arm; I cannot tell whether it was under his coat, nor what size or colour it was - I was on the other side of the way - I believe there are two lodgers in Chester's house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1921">
                  MARGARET 
                  ANN BEST
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1921" type="surname" value="ANN BEST"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1921" type="given" value="MARGARET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1921" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of William Best - I was in Church-street, Spitalfields, that morning, about half-past nine o'clock - I met the prisoner going out of Brick-lane, with some velvet under his arm inside his coat- I said "Halloo," and he said, "Flare up, and you shall have a velvet bonnet" - I said nothing to him, and he ran off.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Could you see the velvet? A. Yes; the front of his coat was open; it was black velvet with white edges.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1922">
                  THOMAS 
                  CHESTER
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1922" type="surname" value="CHESTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1922" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1922" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lost seven yards of velvet that morning, which was worth 2l. 12s. 6d.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1923">
                  THOMAS 
                  GRANT
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1923" type="surname" value="GRANT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1923" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1923" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (police-constable H 76). I produce a certificate of the prisoner's former conviction, which I got at Mr. Clark's office - I know the prisoner is the man (read).</p>
               <p>Witness for the Prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1924">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1924" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1924" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1924" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have known the prisoner two years - on the morning of the 4th of February, about nine o'clock, the prisoner's wife came to my house, and asked me to let him come and finish some work, which I said he should - I put on my hat and went to his house - he was washing himself - he left his house with me, and went to the door of my house; but he did not go in, as he had borrowed a coat of a friend, which he had tied up in a blue and white handkerchief under his arm - I did not see him again till he was in custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-210-person1925">
                  HENRY 
                  PALMER
               <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1925" type="surname" value="PALMER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1925" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-person1925" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lent the prisoner a coat, which he brought and returned to me on the 4th of February, about a quarter past nine o'clock; and he stayed in my shop a quarter of an hour, or twenty minutes.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. The last time I was here, it was a warning to me; and I have got my living ever since by hard work.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340220-210-verdict1198" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-verdict1198" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 25. - <rs id="t18340220-210-punish1199" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340220-210-punish1199" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-210-defend1914 t18340220-210-punish1199"></join>
               Confined for One Year
            </rs>.</p>
